{
  "reasoning": "The analysis begins with the established fact that the individuals initiated a violation of property rights by crossing the border outside a designated port of entry. While their motivation to flee violence is a significant exercise of their own agency, their decision to bypass legal entry and to not seek asylum in two other safe countries transfers the consequences of their choices onto the citizens of the host nation. The core tension is between the migrants' self-determination and the property rights and sovereignty of the nation's citizens. The existing asylum system, with its 2.3-year backlog and overloaded facilities, represents a substantial and prolonged imposition on taxpayer property and creates a state of dependency, which runs counter to the principle of self-reliance. Expedited deportation is the direct and swift consequence of the initial act of trespass. It upholds the principle that individuals are responsible for their actions, respects the integrity of the national border as a property line, and minimizes reliance on a burdensome state apparatus. This reasoning prioritizes individual sovereignty and property rights over collective welfare and international institutional authority.",
  "recommendation": "Initiate expedited deportation proceedings for the entire group, consistent with the standard protocol for illegal entry under 8 U.S.C. § 1325.",
  "valuesApplied": [
    "Property Rights",
    "Individual Agency and Autonomy",
    "Minimizing Reliance on External Authority"
  ],
  "tradeoffsAcknowledged": "This recommendation consciously subordinates the potential safety and welfare of the migrants to the principles of national sovereignty and property rights. There is a tangible risk that individuals with legitimate fears of persecution, who might have qualified for asylum (the 13% statistical average), will be returned to a dangerous environment. This course of action may also conflict with international agreements on refugee rights and could be perceived as inhumane, prioritizing legal formalism over the mitigating circumstances of the individuals involved, including the presence of children."
